The fading “Hit Squad” has a final round to increase the number of qualified Kenyan boxers during the final round of Olympics qualifiers slated for June next year in Paris. Coach Benjamin is optimistic that at least three more Kenyans will qualify for the Olympics.
“There is still hope we shall have at least three more boxers qualify for the next Olympic Games,” Benjamin said.





Heavyweight boxer Morris Okolla sparring at Nairobi Penthouse Gym at View Park Towers on December 12, 2020 during training for Africa Boxing Union (ABU) title fight against Jack "Big Jack" Mulowayi of DR Congo .
Photo credit: Chris Omollo | Nation Media Group


What is almost certain is that sending more boxers to Tokyo will be a tall order for the team unless boxers get international exposure ahead of the final round of qualifiers. 
The team cancelled a planned training camp planned for January in Kazakhstan and Azerbaijan that would have given the boxers the much-needed exposure.
“Sharpening skills at home is not bad but there is need to gauge our skills and techniques with established boxing nations. It is sad that Boxing Federation of Kenya could not secure funds for boxers to train in Europe,” said one of the boxers.
“It wouldn’t make sense for us to go for a local residential training camp and still expect good results in the qualifiers,” said a female pugilist.
In 2016 Olympic Games in Rio de Janeiro,  Rayton Okwiri (welterweight), Peter Mungai (flyweight) and Benson Gicharu (bantamweight) represented Kenya. All of them did not go past the round of 16.



